metadata.name: Feedback Crystal #6
metadata.description:
A "feedback crystal" is a cellular automaton (similar to Conway's Game of Life) where the rules are represented by a randomized kernel. The kernel determines the micro and macro structures that develop in the crystal. The crystals are grown from "seed" pixels (in this artwork, the white outline and white center pixel provide the seed).

Sometimes the patterns are chaotic, sometimes they are stable. If you are lucky, a pattern will be generated "on the edge of chaos" that mixes stability and chaos in an emergent complex system. These are rare. In addition, a small number of artworks will result in "dead" crystals that do not grow. These are also rare, but there is a chance that your crystal will be a mostly black square.

Each piece is composed of 3 different randomly generated kernels that sweep outwards from the center.

metadata.name: Sketchbook Splash #358
metadata.description:
A splash of color on some scribbled shapes.

There are several keybindings to modify the image:
'1' - Toggles watercolors
'2' - Toggles overlaying constrast shapes 
'3' - Toggles sketch outlines
'4' - Toggles shape/splatter clipping (will fill the entire canvas with watercolor!)
'B' - Cycles borders; black, white, all colors in the palette being used, and no border

Play around to find something you like, and then press 'S' to download a copy of your image. 
You can also modify the URL parameters at the end of the URL to change the size of the image, such as &x=2560&y=1440. Keep in mind that this will result in a slightly different image, but colors/shapes/general layout will remain the same. The default size is 2048x2048.

metadata.name: Hash Effects #97
metadata.description:
Hash Effects is an introspective graphical performance that discovers its own abstract origins and morphs it into concrete forms.

The origins of these artworks lie within the transaction hash that results from minting a unique edition of the artwork. Each graphical trait in the artwork is controlled by this origin, so in essence the transaction hash is responsible for the entire artwork.

While most generative artworks hide their transaction hash in abstraction, Hash Effects shows it front and center. Each unique artwork celebrates its own transaction hash as a graphical element that morphs into various shapes over different animation scenes.

metadata.name: BRUTALISM #28
metadata.description:
What Is Brutalism?
Brutalism is a style of architecture that lasted from the 1950s-1970s, and it was characterized by simple, block-like, hulking concrete structures, with an emphasis on materials, textures and construction, producing highly expressive forms.

The buildings are characterised by their massive, monolithic and ‘blocky’ appearance with a rigid geometric style and large-scale use of poured concrete.

Brutalism began to fade out in the 1980s, where it increasingly came to be regarded as cold, alienating and unfit for humans. It turned out that concrete had an allure of indestructibility but deteriorated from the inside, making it difficult to maintain and prone to crumbling and water damage as it aged.

In the years since, the world has been divided into those who think that Brutalist buildings are eyesores that should be demolished and those who find these vintage but not yet historic buildings architectural masterpieces to be cherished and preserved. 

--------------------------------------------------------
About the work:
This work was built entirely with code using only math, logic and 2D shapes to create light, shadow and perspective.

--------------------------------------------------------
Features:
"Canvas Orientation": Square, Portrait
"Building Size": Large, Medium, Small
"Time of day": Day, Night
"Sun/Moon": True, False
"Palette": 23 palettes
"Floors": 3, 4
"Clouds": True, False

--------------------------------------------------------
Constrols in live mode:
On desktop: Press 's' or 'S' to save as PNG (2622x3720 or 3720x3720)
On mobile: Touch the screen to save as PNG (2622x3720 or 3720x3720)

Artwork created with p5.js and love.
